    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-43442">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43442" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43442">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43442">gregelin</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43442" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43442" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Joel Natividad, there might be an important nuance to your point on agencies previously building their own payroll and HR systems.  </p>
<p>I was at the Federal Communication Commission from 2010 to 2013 in the role of Chief Data Officer. I can give further testimony to Matt&#8217;s assertion: &#8220;Computing used to be ancillary to an organization’s mission. Now it’s central to it.&#8221;</p>
<p>Paying employees is standardized. Parts of HR are standardized, but then again human resources are an organization&#8217;s most valuable asset. To Matt&#8217;s point &#8220;immense time&#8221; is required to find the right people for an organization. CFPB remolded and extended the HR process (and therefore the &#8220;system&#8221;) to better support its mission goals and its commitment to quality. </p>
<p>The received wisdom on &#8220;don&#8217;t re-invent the wheel&#8221; does not mean all tires perform equally well on all cars and all terrain. Great tech starts with great elements and assembles optimized solutions through continuous measurement and improvement.  </p>
<p>I agree with your point regarding how APIs can better empower in-house teams.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-43446">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-43446" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-43446">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-43446">john scott</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-43446" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-43446" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>One question I&#8217;ve been wrestling with is how long should qualified IT/software folk be government employees? Working in the government cause skills to degrade and I&#8217;ve seen it be very, very hard for smart and very talented developers to keep their skills current + I think a majority of developers would love to jump into the government to help out, solve tough problems and then move forward to other newer opportunities. Matthew hits upon the really hard problem of how best to churn any type of smart and motivated developers, etc. into and out of the government in a timely fashion is really needed. It can&#8217;t take 6+ months to get hired.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
            </ul>


        </div>

    </div>

